<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="163" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1217,1998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1289,1314]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Description</emphasis>
. Massive rounded sponge with low mounds (
<figureCitation box="[875,945,1289,1314]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1448,1470]" captionTargetBox="[288,1299,197,1423]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[288,1299,195,1423]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Strongylacidon bermuda (de Laubenfels 1950): A. Specimen preserved in alcohol. B. Detail of densely packed tracts of strongyles forming a round mesh. C. Common strongyles in LM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238824/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
Fig. 
<number box="[931,945,1290,1314]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
A), 
<quantity box="[992,1051,1289,1314]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
in diameter and 
<quantity box="[1256,1315,1290,1314]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
in height. Surface is markedly conulose. These protuberance-like conules are mainly round and evenly distributed all over the surface, 
<quantity box="[245,380,1361,1386]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.5 mm</quantity>
in height, 
<quantity box="[498,591,1362,1386]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
apart. Several oscules mainly on top of the sponge are 
<quantity box="[1205,1298,1361,1386]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Consistency is firm but slightly compressible. A not so easily detachable thin dermis is visible; with a reticulate pattern of pigmented granules enclosing the pore fields. Color 
<emphasis box="[852,928,1434,1457]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">in vivo</emphasis>
is black with green subectosomal veins, dark violet or black in alcohol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1217,1998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,1505,1530]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Skeleton</emphasis>
. Without ectosomal skeleton. The choanosomal skeleton consists of poorly defined reticulation made by densely packed tracts of spicules outlining round to irregular meshes (
<figureCitation box="[966,1033,1541,1566]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1448,1470]" captionTargetBox="[288,1299,197,1423]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[288,1299,195,1423]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Strongylacidon bermuda (de Laubenfels 1950): A. Specimen preserved in alcohol. B. Detail of densely packed tracts of strongyles forming a round mesh. C. Common strongyles in LM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238824/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
Fig. 
<number box="[1018,1033,1542,1566]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Ill-defined tracts 
<number box="[1265,1364,1541,1566]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="225.0" valueMax="300.0" valueMin="150.0">150–300</number>
µm in thickness, several of which conform a trellis work towards the surface, making up those conules or tuberculate protuberances of the surface. Connective tracts 
<number box="[683,753,1614,1638]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="50.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="30.0">30–70</number>
µm thick, with abundant but loose single strongyles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1217,1998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1649,1674]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Spicules</emphasis>
. Abundant straight, uniform and slender strongyles, with isodiametric endings 
<number box="[1200,1319,1649,1674]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="188.3" valueMax="218.0" valueMin="158.6">158.6–218</number>
× 
<number box="[1352,1436,1650,1674]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="2.05" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="1.3">1.3–2.8</number>
µm (
<figureCitation box="[204,271,1685,1710]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1448,1470]" captionTargetBox="[288,1299,197,1423]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[288,1299,195,1423]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Strongylacidon bermuda (de Laubenfels 1950): A. Specimen preserved in alcohol. B. Detail of densely packed tracts of strongyles forming a round mesh. C. Common strongyles in LM." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238824/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
Fig. 
<number box="[256,271,1686,1710]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C), some with rod shaped, and loop shaped ends. Microscleres are absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="163" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1217,1998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,490,1721,1746]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[503,606,1721,1746]" class="Demospongiae" family="Dendoricellidae" genus="Fibulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="180" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<collectingCountry box="[503,606,1721,1746]" name="Bermuda" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
(de 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels" box="[655,846,1721,1746]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1950) The Porifera of the Bermuda Archipelago. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 27, 1 - 154. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1950. tb 00227. x" type="journal article" year="1950">
Laubenfels 
<number box="[786,846,1721,1746]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="1950.0">1950</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Inhabits reef environments and reported up to 
<quantity box="[1380,1436,1721,1746]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
in depth. This is the first record for the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[679,769,1757,1782]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="163" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1217,1998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1793,1818]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[321,597,1793,1818]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<emphasis box="[321,597,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Strongylacidon bermuda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been recorded again since its original description by de 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1950) The Porifera of the Bermuda Archipelago. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 27, 1 - 154. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1950. tb 00227. x" type="journal article" year="1950">
Laubenfels (
<number box="[159,217,1829,1854]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="1950.0">1950</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
in Harrington Sound, 
<taxonomicName box="[488,594,1829,1854]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="180" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<collectingCountry box="[488,594,1829,1854]" name="Bermuda" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
, where it was fairly common. The features described for 
<taxonomicName box="[1261,1392,1829,1854]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<emphasis box="[1261,1392,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">S. bermuda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are consistent with the present material. The massive habit is rather common for 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1243,1865,1890]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<emphasis box="[1107,1243,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">S. bermuda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although some differences emerge: 
<number box="[393,405,1902,1926]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="1.0">1</number>
) massive with a tendency to grow up into rounded lobes, hardly called digitate (de 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels" box="[151,342,1937,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1950) The Porifera of the Bermuda Archipelago. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 27, 1 - 154. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1950. tb 00227. x" type="journal article" year="1950">
Laubenfels 
<number box="[282,342,1937,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="1950.0">1950</number>
</bibRefCitation>
); 
<number box="[361,376,1938,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="2.0">2</number>
) massive with rounded lobes or low tubes (
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler" box="[859,1197,1937,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" refString="Rutzler, K. (1986) Phylum Porifera (sponges). In: Sterrer, W. (Ed.), Marine Fauna and Flora of Bermuda. John Wiley T Sons, New York, pp. 111 - 127." type="book chapter" year="1986">
Rützler 
<number box="[950,1010,1937,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="1986.0">1986</number>
:Fig. 
<number box="[1059,1089,1937,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="32.0">32</number>
; as 
<taxonomicName box="[1130,1197,1937,1962]" class="Demospongiae" family="Esperiopsidae" genus="Ulosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1130,1197,1937,1962]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="163">Ulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<number box="[1260,1274,1938,1962]" pageId="12" pageNumber="163" value="3.0">3</number>
) massive with low mounds (present work).
</paragraph>
